","Rosslyn Castle, Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland":"Roslin, Midlothian, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1214–1270":"1214–1270","1213–1299":"1213–1299","1216–1270":"1216–1270","1220–1248":"1220–1248","1232–1271":"1232–1271","1260–1297":"1260–1297","1192–1214":"1192–1214","1197–Female":"1197–Overleden","before 1213":"vóór 1213","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1192":"1192","April 1248":"april 1248","1216":"1216","1248":"1248","1214":"1214","1213":"1213","1299":"1299","1232":"1232","from 1243 to 1270":"van 1243 to 1270","Rosslyn Castle, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland":"Roslin, Midlothian, Schotland","Rosslyn Castle, Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland":"Roslin, Midlothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1214–1270":"1214–1270","1213–1299":"1213–1299","1216–1270":"1216–1270","1220–1248":"1220–1248","1232–1271":"1232–1271","1260–1297":"1260–1297","1192–1214":"1192–1214","1197–Female":"1197–Deceased","before 1213":"before 1213","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1192":"1192","April 1248":"April 1248","1216":"1216","1248":"1248","1214":"1214","1213":"1213","1299":"1299","1232":"1232","from 1243 to 1270":"from 1243 to 1270","Rosslyn Castle, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland":"Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland","Rosslyn Castle, Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland":"Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sinclair","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Saint-Clair-sur-Elle (Manche), so called from the dedication of its church to Saint Clarus (see   Clare   3).","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname.","History: The Scottish family <i>Sinclair</i> (see 1 above) came to southern Scotland in the twelfth century from Huntingdonshire with the de Morvilles. Descendants of these Sinclairs became earls of Caithness in the 15th century. The frequency of the surname in Caithness and Orkney is largely due to the adoption by tenants of the name of their overlord."],"variants":[{"name":"Clare","meanings":["Irish (Clare, Wicklow, and Wexford): habitational name from Clare in Suffolk (an eastern county of England), the center of a major Norman baronial estate since the Norman Conquest. The English placename probably originated as a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright, gentle, or warm’. The surname is not from the Irish county name <i>Clare</i>, which is either from the surname or from a place called with Gaelic <i>clár</i> ‘plank bridge’. Another Norman surname in the southeast of Ireland was <i>de Clere</i>, from Clères in Seine-Maritime (France), named from the local river.","English and French: from the Middle English, Old French female personal name <i>Cla(i)re</i> (from Latin <i>Clara</i>, from <i>clarus</i> ‘clear, bright, famous’) which achieved some popularity, greater elsewhere in Europe than in England, through the fame of Saint Clare of Assisi (see   Chiara  ). The English surname seems to have been interchangeable with   Clear   1.","English: occupational name from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>cley</i> ‘clay’. The work of medieval clayers involved plastering a framework of interwoven twigs with mud to produce wattle-and-daub work."]},{"name":"St. Clair","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Sinclair  . This is also a French Canadian and American French altered form of the same surname.","French (<b>Saint-Clair</b>): habitational name from any of several places, e.g. in Normandy, named Saint-Clair (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Clarus). Compare   Saintclair  .","Haitian (also <b>Saint-Clair</b>): ornamental name or nickname, perhaps ironic, composed of French <i>saint</i> ‘saint’ or ‘holy’ and <i>clair</i> ‘clear’ or ‘lightness’. Alternatively, perhaps of the same French origin as 2 above. Compare   Saintclair  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Sinclair 5th Lord of Rosslyn was born in 1214, in Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Henry Sinclair 2nd Baron of Roslin, was 22 and his mother, Katherine Strathearn, was 18. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Margaret Mar. He registered for military service in 1262. He died in 1270, in his hometown, at the age of 56, and was buried in Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland."},"et":{"1214–1270":"1214–1270","1213–1299":"1213–1299","1216–1270":"1216–1270","1220–1248":"1220–1248","1232–1271":"1232–1271","1260–1297":"1260–1297","1192–1214":"1192–1214","1197–Female":"1197–Surnud","before 1213":"enne 1213","1297":"1297","1220":"1220","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1192":"1192","April 1248":"aprill 1248","1216":"1216","1248":"1248","1214":"1214","1213":"1213","1299":"1299","1232":"1232","from 1243 to 1270":"1243 kuni 1270","Rosslyn Castle, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland":"Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland","Rosslyn Castle, Roslin, Midlothian, Scotland":"Roslin, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1214–1270":"1214–1270","1213–1299":"1213–1299","1216–1270":"1216–1270","1220–1248":"1220–1248","1